 Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":2,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":12,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrix de Vesci was born in 1094, in Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, her father, Ivo de Vesci, Lord of Alnwick, was 29 and her mother, Ada Tyson, was 31. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Eustace fitz John. She died in 1123, in Knaresborough, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 29, and was buried in Alnwick, Northumberland, England."},"et":{"1094–1123":"1094–1123","1100–1157":"1100–1157","1120–1220":"1120–1220","1125–1183":"1125–1183","–1175":"–1175","1065–1157":"1065–1157","1063–1120":"1063–1120","1220":"1220","1120":"1120","1065":"1065","1175":"1175","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1063":"1063","1183":"1183","1094":"1094","1106":"1106","1